 Legislatures, too, had begun to chip away at the rule. A number of states, in the late nineteenth century, modified or abolished the rule, either for railroads or more generally. Kansas, for example, enacted a statute in 1874 which made railroads in that state \u8220\'93liable for all damages done to any employee ... in consequence of any negligence\u8221\'94 of the railroad\u8217\'92s agents.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F26539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
