\~}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af9\afs24\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af3\loch\ql\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\ltrpar\cf0\f3\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\qj\fi0\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0{\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EUUAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EUUAE_1}By this time, however, the fellow-servant rule was in trouble. It had been battered by court decisions. Piecemeal legislation had made some inroads. It had been subjected to withering criticism. Change had come about even before Eastman published her book. The Federal Employers\u8217\'92 Liability Act (hereinafter \u8220\'93FELA\u8221\'94) did away with the fellow-servant rule for railroad workers; the statute also cut back the defense of contributory negligence}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F32539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F32539209744_ID0EJVAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F32539209744_ID0EJVAE_1}32}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 The United States Supreme Court, in a narrow and technical decision, struck down this statute; but congress amended the law in 1908; and the Supreme Court upheld this version of the law.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F33539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F33539209744_ID0EOVAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F33539209744_ID0EOVAE_1}33}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 Under FELA, railroads were liable for any deaths or injuries resulting from the negligence of employees.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F34539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F34539209744_ID0ETVAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F34539209744_ID0ETVAE_1}34}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 The Jones Act of 1920 provided that a seaman injured or killed \u8220\'93in the course of employment\u8221\'94 had the same rights as against an employer as railroad workers.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F35539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F35539209744_ID0EYVAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F35539209744_ID0EYVAE_1}35}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 These were, of course, federal laws, and applied only to interstate and admiralty workers. They essentially retained the common law tort system, but stripped away the more egregious rules, including the fellow-servant rule, that blocked injured workers from suing their employers successfully.}
