\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af9\afs24\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af3\loch\ql\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\ltrpar\cf0\f3\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\qj\fi0\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0{\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EWXAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EWXAE_1}In fact, such a law soon became a reality in the states. Workers\u8217\'92 compensation laws replaced the fellow-servant rule, along with other rules that had made tort law so stingy, so unpredictable, and so deficient in social justice. Workers\u8217\'92 compensation, in essence, was a no-fault system for victims of industrial accidents.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F40539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F40539209744_ID0EEYAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F40539209744_ID0EEYAE_1}40}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 The basic idea was simple: a person injured on the job would be entitled to compensation. The fellow-servant rule was abolished. So was the defense of contributory negligence. A tired and overworked employee, who let his guard slip, and was injured, no longer lost any hope of compensation.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af9\afs24\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af3\loch\ql\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\ltrpar\cf0\f3\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\qj\fi0\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\sb0\sa0{\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5
\~}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af9\afs24\alang1081 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe2052\hich\af3\loch\ql\nowidctlpar\hyphpar0\ltrpar\cf0\f3\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af8\langfe2052\qj\fi0\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0{\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EWYAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EWYAE_1}But there were obstacles in the way: opposition to the idea in general, and with regard to certain details. Unlike Great Britain, where courts had no power of judicial review (for better or for worse), courts in the United States had such a power; they could declare statutes unconstitutional; and in the late nineteenth and early twentieth century, they were hardly bashful about using this power. Any piece of major legislation had to run the gamut of judicial review. New York was the first state to pass a compensation law, in 1910, but the top court in New York struck the statute down in 1911.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F41539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F41539209744_ID0EHZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F41539209744_ID0EHZAE_1}41}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 This, however, turned out to be only a temporary setback. The New York Constitution was amended to meet the courts\u8217\'92 objections. In other states, the statutes had less trouble in court. The United States Supreme Court also rejected objections to compensation statutes, in a case decided in 1917.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F42539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F42539209744_ID0EVZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F42539209744_ID0EVZAE_1}42}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 In the decade between 1910 and 1920, workers\u8217\'92 compensation laws were enacted in most of the states. States of the deep south held out for a while; Mississippi was the last; and it fell in line in 1948.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F43539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F43539209744_ID0E4ZAE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F43539209744_ID0E4ZAE_1}43}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 To be sure, in every state, passage was something of a struggle, if not on the principle itself, then on the form. But, by this time, it was a striking fact that management, as well as labor, was more or less on board in many of the states. In Wisconsin, for example, \u8220\'93large employers throughout the state lined up solidly behind the workmen\u8217\'92s compensation bill;\u8221\'94 and the legislature adopted a law in 1911 by a \u8220\'93lopsided\u8221\'94 vote.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F44539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F44539209744_ID0EW1AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F44539209744_ID0EW1AE_1}44}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 In 1910, a survey conducted by the National Association of Manufacturers found that 95% of the businesses surveyed supported some sort of compensation plan.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F45539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F45539209744_ID0E21AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F45539209744_ID0E21AE_1}45}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 And in 1911, the National Association of Manufacturers \u8220\'93fully endorsed workers\u8217\'92 compensation\u8221\'94}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F46539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F46539209744_ID0E51AE_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F46539209744_ID0E51AE_1}46}}}}
