{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EBAAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EBAAG_1}The nineteenth century was an age of science and technology. It was the century of the railroad, the telegraph, the telephone; later in the century came the wireless; and the first steps toward the development of the automobile. It was also the century of Darwin. It was an age of innovation and improvement in manufacturing. All of this had a profound impact on culture. New technologies and new discoveries changed the way people looked at the world around them. As people came to understand natural forces, as science marched on, the culture changed. Knowledge affected the level of social demands: demands to }{\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
do}{\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 something. Nothing, of course, could be done about the earth\u8217\'92s orbit or the phases of the moon; but accidents and diseases were another matter. Science injected into society new ideas about causes of diseases, catastrophes, and \u8220\'93accidents\u8221\'94 Science was the enemy of fatalism. It was the enemy of half-baked ideas about causes and effects. What, for example, explained the outbreak of epidemics? Was it foul air? Was it divine retribution for sin? In the nineteenth century, the development of the \u8220\'93germ theory\u8221\'94 put forward a new and different answer}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F55539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F55539209744_ID0EYBAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F55539209744_ID0EYBAG_1}55}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 Cholera, for example, was no longer a mysterious killer that exploded into a community without warning. Microscopic creatures (\u8220\'93germs\u8221\'94) were polluting the water supply: that was the source of cholera epidemics}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F56539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F56539209744_ID0E5BAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F56539209744_ID0E5BAG_1}56}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 As early as 1854, a British scientist, John Snow, became aware of the role of bad water}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F57539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F57539209744_ID0EBCAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F57539209744_ID0EBCAG_1}57}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 Londoners who used one water pump died in droves; those who used water from a cleaner source did not}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F58539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F58539209744_ID0EECAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F58539209744_ID0EECAG_1}58}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 Adding chlorine to the water supply gave society control over cholera}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F59539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F59539209744_ID0EHCAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F59539209744_ID0EHCAG_1}59}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 Understanding that polluted water caused cholera, and that \u8220\'93germs\u8221\'94 were the source of the pollution, changed attitudes toward the disease.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F60539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F60539209744_ID0EMCAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F60539209744_ID0EMCAG_1}60}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 This led to demands for improvements in sanitation, in public health; chlorine could conquer the \u8220\'93germs\u8221\'94 Much could be done; but only government could do it.}
