{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EPDAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EPDAG_1}The first workers\u8217\'92 compensation laws, however, were in many ways weaker and more tentative than the compensation laws of today. Kansas, for example, enacted a compensation law in 1911.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F62539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F62539209744_ID0E1DAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F62539209744_ID0E1DAG_1}62}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 It was, in the first place, elective: both employers and employees could decide to come under the law; or remain outside. The law applied only to employers with 15 or more employees and it applied only to accidents in dangerous occupations--manufacturing, mining, quarrying, work at natural gas plants for example--along with jobs that made use of dangerous explosives or inflammable materials. There were similar provisions in the Illinois law of 1911, which listed occupations which were \u8220\'93especially dangerous,\u8221\'94 like quarrying, and work with \u8220\'93explosive materials,\u8221\'94 posing \u8220\'93extraordinary risks to life and limb\u8221\'94}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F63539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F63539209744_ID0EREAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F63539209744_ID0EREAG_1}63}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 The statute in Washington state (1911) applied to all \u8220\'93inherently hazardous works and occupations\u8221\'94}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F64539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F64539209744_ID0EUEAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F64539209744_ID0EUEAG_1}64}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 Not all of the statutes were limited in this way: the California law, for example, also enacted in 1911, was elective (like the Kansas law), but it applied to industry in general.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F65539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F65539209744_ID0EZEAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F65539209744_ID0EZEAG_1}65}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 The Ohio law, also of 1911, was another elective law; both companies and workers could opt out.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F66539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F66539209744_ID0E5EAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F66539209744_ID0E5EAG_1}66}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 But within a few years, the legislature amended the law, and workers\u8217\'92 compensation became mandatory for employers.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F67539209744_1" }{\fldrslt {\hich\af5\loch\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\super\f5\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\cf19\strike0\super\fs16\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F67539209744_ID0EDFAG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F67539209744_ID0EDFAG_1}67}{}}}\hich\af5\loch\cf19\strike0\fs20\i0\ulnone\ulc0\b0\f5\loch
 This soon became the norm in state after state.}
